      <h1 class="font-heading text-3xl sm:text-4xl md:text-5xl leading-tight">How Much Does Hardwood Flooring Cost in Houston? (2026 Guide)</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-brand-ink/70 text-sm">Published May 2026 · By Joey Jamail</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Article body -->
  <article class="container mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pb-16 max-w-3xl text-brand-ink/90 leading-relaxed text-[1.0625rem]">

    <p>Short answer first, because that's what you came here for: in Houston in 2026, a professionally installed hardwood floor typically costs <strong>$11 to $22 per square foot</strong>, with most whole-home projects landing somewhere in the middle. That's the all-in number — material, labor, demo, subfloor prep, transitions, and trim.</p>

    <p class="mt-4">If you want a more specific number for your house, <a href="/contact" class="text-brand-brass hover:underline font-semibold">order a free sample box</a> or <a href={BOOKING_URL} target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" class="text-brand-brass hover:underline font-semibold">book a 30-minute consultation</a> and we'll give you a written estimate within 48 hours. If you want to understand what drives the cost so you can budget intelligently, keep reading.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">The Houston hardwood flooring cost breakdown</h2>
    <p>A real installed cost has five pieces. National averages won't help you — Houston has its own labor market, its own slab-on-grade construction quirks, and its own humidity-driven product preferences. Here's what each piece actually costs in this market in 2026:</p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">1. Material — $4 to $14 per square foot</h3>
    <p>This is the floor itself. The range is wide because hardwood spans a huge quality spectrum.</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>$4–$6/sq ft — Big-box engineered oak:</strong> 3" wide, 3mm wear layer, factory finish, made overseas with minimal quality control. Fine for a rental or flip. Not what we install.</li>
      <li><strong>$6–$10/sq ft — Mid-tier engineered hardwood:</strong> 5"–7" wide, 2–3mm wear layer, decent finish. Most of what you'll see at flooring chains.</li>
      <li><strong>$10–$14/sq ft — Premium engineered, European-milled:</strong> 7"+ wide planks, 4mm sawn-face wear layer, hand-finished, low-VOC. This is what we install, and what most designer-driven Houston homes use today.</li>
      <li><strong>$14+/sq ft — Solid hardwood, reclaimed, or custom:</strong> Rare in Houston because of humidity.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-4">We use engineered European white oak almost exclusively for one practical reason: <strong>Houston humidity</strong>. Solid hardwood expands and contracts more aggressively than engineered hardwood, which can cup, gap, or buckle in our climate. The engineered construction uses a stable plywood core under the real-oak wear layer, so it stays flat through the 90°F-to-40°F humidity swings between July and January.</p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">2. Labor — $5 to $9 per square foot</h3>
    <p>This is what installation actually costs in Houston, including a properly trained crew, dust containment, moisture testing, and warranty-backed work.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">You'll see "cheap" installers quote $2–$3 per square foot. What you usually get for that price: a crew that doesn't moisture-test the slab (a major cause of failures in Houston), uses the wrong adhesive, takes shortcuts on transitions, and won't be reachable when a problem shows up six months later.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">Real, code-correct installation in Houston runs $5–$9 per square foot for engineered hardwood, depending on:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>Glue-down on concrete slab</strong> (most Houston homes — moderate cost)</li>
      <li><strong>Floating over underlayment</strong> (faster, slightly less)</li>
      <li><strong>Nail-down over plywood subfloor</strong> (older Houston homes — slightly more)</li>
      <li><strong>Diagonal or herringbone patterns</strong> (more labor, +$2–$5/sq ft)</li>
      <li><strong>Stairs and complex transitions</strong> (priced separately)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">3. Demo and disposal — $1 to $3 per square foot</h3>
    <p>If you're replacing existing tile, carpet, laminate, or old hardwood, that material has to come out, and that adds cost.</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>Carpet removal:</strong> ~$1/sq ft, cheap and fast</li>
      <li><strong>Laminate or floating LVP:</strong> ~$1.50/sq ft</li>
      <li><strong>Glued-down vinyl or hardwood:</strong> $2–$3/sq ft (real labor to scrape adhesive)</li>
      <li><strong>Tile demo:</strong> $3–$5/sq ft (worst case — old thinset has to come off the slab)</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">A lot of Houston homes have ceramic tile downstairs from the 90s and 2000s, and that tile demo is often the single biggest "surprise" line item people don't budget for. Get a real quote that includes demo — don't accept a price that's "just for the install."</p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">4. Subfloor prep — $0 to $4 per square foot</h3>
    <p>This is the wild card. Until we look at your subfloor, no installer can promise a number. Common Houston issues:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>Moisture issues:</strong> Concrete slabs in Houston routinely test high for moisture. If the reading is over 4 lbs/sqft/24hr (or 75% RH), the slab needs a moisture-mitigation coating before adhesive — adds about $1–$2/sq ft.</li>
      <li><strong>Uneven slab:</strong> Any slab variation over 3/16" in 10 feet has to be leveled with self-leveling compound. Adds $1–$2/sq ft.</li>
      <li><strong>Bad existing adhesive:</strong> Glue residue from old flooring has to be ground off the slab. Slow work.</li>
      <li><strong>Damaged subfloor (upstairs):</strong> Soft, water-damaged, or squeaky plywood subfloors need patches.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">A reputable installer will moisture-test and measure your subfloor before quoting, and will give you a number that includes any prep they know is needed.</p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">5. Trim, transitions, and finish work — $1 to $2 per square foot</h3>
    <p>This is the work that separates a hardwood install that "looks finished" from one that doesn't. Quarter-round, T-moldings, reducers, stair-nose pieces, threshold transitions, undercut door jambs, baseboards (if removed/replaced), and the prep work to make it all sit flush.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">Cheap installers skip this. We don't. It's the difference between a $40,000 floor that looks like it came with the house, and one that looks like it was added later.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">Total: real Houston project examples</h2>
    <p>Three project profiles we see weekly:</p>

    <div class="mt-6 rounded-2xl bg-brand-ivory p-6">
      <h3 class="font-heading text-lg text-brand-coal mb-2">Example 1: 1,400 sq ft inner-loop bungalow, downstairs only</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm list-disc pl-6">
        <li>Material (mid-tier European oak, 7" plank): $11/sq ft × 1,400 = $15,400</li>
        <li>Demo (existing carpet): $1/sq ft × 1,400 = $1,400</li>
        <li>Subfloor prep (minor leveling): $0.50/sq ft × 1,400 = $700</li>
        <li>Labor (glue-down on slab): $6/sq ft × 1,400 = $8,400</li>
        <li>Trim and transitions: $1/sq ft × 1,400 = $1,400</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="mt-3 font-semibold text-brand-coal">Total: ~$27,300 — roughly $19.50/sq ft installed</p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-4 rounded-2xl bg-brand-ivory p-6">
      <h3 class="font-heading text-lg text-brand-coal mb-2">Example 2: 2,800 sq ft Memorial home, full downstairs replacement</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm list-disc pl-6">
        <li>Material (premium European oak, hand-finished): $13/sq ft × 2,800 = $36,400</li>
        <li>Demo (existing ceramic tile): $3.50/sq ft × 2,800 = $9,800</li>
        <li>Subfloor prep (moisture mitigation + leveling): $1.50/sq ft × 2,800 = $4,200</li>
        <li>Labor: $7/sq ft × 2,800 = $19,600</li>
        <li>Trim, transitions, baseboards: $1.50/sq ft × 2,800 = $4,200</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="mt-3 font-semibold text-brand-coal">Total: ~$74,200 — roughly $26.50/sq ft installed (high end because of tile demo)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-4 rounded-2xl bg-brand-ivory p-6">
      <h3 class="font-heading text-lg text-brand-coal mb-2">Example 3: 4,500 sq ft new-construction Woodlands home</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm list-disc pl-6">
        <li>Material (premium European oak, wide plank): $12/sq ft × 4,500 = $54,000</li>
        <li>Demo: $0 (new construction)</li>
        <li>Subfloor prep (clean slab, builder-grade): $0.50/sq ft × 4,500 = $2,250</li>
        <li>Labor: $6/sq ft × 4,500 = $27,000</li>
        <li>Trim and transitions: $1/sq ft × 4,500 = $4,500</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="mt-3 font-semibold text-brand-coal">Total: ~$87,750 — roughly $19.50/sq ft installed</p>
    </div>

    <p class="mt-6">These are real ballparks. Your number could be higher or lower. The point is to <strong>budget the all-in cost, not just the material</strong>.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">What makes hardwood cost more in Houston than in other cities</h2>
    <p>A few Houston-specific factors push our prices a bit above the U.S. average:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>Slab-on-grade construction:</strong> Almost every Houston home is built on a concrete slab, which means glue-down installation (more labor) and moisture testing (extra step) versus nail-down over plywood.</li>
      <li><strong>Humidity and moisture mitigation:</strong> We routinely have to add moisture-mitigation coatings that homes in drier climates skip entirely.</li>
      <li><strong>Engineered-only material preference:</strong> Solid hardwood works in Denver. In Houston, it fails. Engineered hardwood costs slightly more for an equivalent visual.</li>
      <li><strong>Labor demand:</strong> Houston construction has been booming for a decade. Skilled flooring labor is in demand and priced accordingly.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">What makes hardwood cost less</h2>
    <p>You can pull the all-in cost down without compromising quality by:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>Choosing a single floor for the entire downstairs</strong> (eliminates transitions, reduces waste, simplifies labor)</li>
      <li><strong>Keeping plank width to 7" instead of 9"+</strong> (wider planks are pricier)</li>
      <li><strong>Picking a factory-finished floor</strong> (vs. site-finished, which adds days and dollars)</li>
      <li><strong>Skipping demo by doing it yourself</strong> (only if you actually know how — most people overestimate this)</li>
      <li><strong>Scheduling in our slower season</strong> (December–February, our crews have more open dates and we can be flexible on timing)</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">What about LVP, laminate, or "fake" wood?</h2>
    <p>Worth the comparison if you're budget-constrained:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>Luxury vinyl plank (LVP):</strong> $7–$13/sq ft installed in Houston. Looks convincingly like hardwood at 6 feet, less so at 2 feet. Waterproof. Doesn't add resale value the way real hardwood does. Wears more visibly over 5–10 years.</li>
      <li><strong>Laminate:</strong> $5–$9/sq ft installed. Cheaper but feels and sounds hollow underfoot. Cannot be refinished.</li>
      <li><strong>Tile that looks like wood:</strong> $9–$15/sq ft installed. Durable but cold and hard.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">Real hardwood is the only one of these that's still in the house — and still worth money — in 30 years. The lifetime cost of a good hardwood floor is often lower than the alternatives.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">How to get an actual price for your house</h2>
    <p>Three things drive the gap between a number on a blog post and a number on a quote:</p>
    <ol class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-decimal pl-6">
      <li><strong>Square footage</strong> (which a tape measure or floor plan answers in 10 minutes)</li>
      <li><strong>Subfloor condition</strong> (which we have to look at)</li>
      <li><strong>Material you actually choose</strong> (which is why we ship free samples)</li>
    </ol>
    <p class="mt-3">Here's how to get to a real number fast:</p>
    <ol class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-decimal pl-6">
      <li><strong>Order a free sample box</strong> — pick up to 6 finishes, we ship them to your door, you look at them in your actual light.</li>
      <li><strong>Book a free in-home consultation</strong> — we come measure, look at your subfloor, and quote in writing within 48 hours.</li>
      <li><strong>Compare quotes</strong> — we encourage homeowners to get 2–3 quotes. Make sure they're all all-inclusive (material + labor + demo + prep + trim). Apples to apples.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">Bottom line</h2>
    <p>For a quality, professionally-installed hardwood floor in Houston in 2026, budget <strong>$15–$25 per square foot all-in</strong> for most homes. Cheaper than that and you're probably getting a corner cut somewhere that will cost you in five years. Significantly more than that and you're probably overpaying — unless you're going custom-milled, reclaimed, or solid-only.</p>

